## Budget Tiers: What You Actually Get at Every Price Point

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Budget</th><th>Best Natural Diamond</th><th>Best Lab Diamond</th><th>Setting</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>$2,000–$3,500</strong></td><td>0.7–0.9ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent</td><td>1.5ct D-IF IGI Ideal ($2,930 stone only)</td><td>14k white gold solitaire ($470)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>$3,500–$6,000</strong></td><td>1ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent ($3,230 stone + $470–$1,200 setting)</td><td>2ct D-VVS1 IGI Ideal ($2,810 stone + $700 pavé setting)</td><td>14k gold solitaire or entry pavé</td></tr><tr><td><strong>$6,000–$12,000</strong></td><td>1.5ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent (~$7,800 stone + setting)</td><td>3ct D-IF IGI Ideal ($11,770 stone + $700 setting = ~$12,470)</td><td>14k/18k gold or platinum solitaire</td></tr><tr><td><strong>$12,000–$20,000</strong></td><td>2ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent ($16,490 stone + setting)</td><td>4ct E-IF IGI Ideal ($12,320 stone + setting = ~$13,020)</td><td>Platinum solitaire or cathedral pavé</td></tr><tr><td><strong>$20,000+</strong></td><td>2.5ct–3ct G-VS2 GIA Excellent</td><td>4ct D-IF IGI Ideal ($20,250 stone + setting)</td><td>Platinum designer setting</td></tr></tbody></table>

At every budget level, the correct strategy is identical: buy the best possible cut at the chosen carat weight, set the grade to G-VS2 natural or D-IF lab, and use remaining budget for the setting. The setting is the last allocation, not the first. Buyers who pick a setting first and then find a diamond to fit the remaining budget consistently underbuy on cut quality.

